Participants were divided into groups of four, each with 20 MU, and had to decide whether to allocate it to a 'private account' or a 'group project'.
Private account income: The MU invested in the private account is directly converted into income, meaning 1 MU invested yields 1 MU earned, with only the investor benefiting.
Group project income: The total project contribution of all members multiplied by 0.4, and the result is evenly distributed to each group member (i.e., each person's income from the project = total contribution × 0.4).
Total income = Private account income (20 MU-individual project contribution) + Project income (total contribution × 0.4).
All decisions are made anonymously, and participants are not allowed to communicate.
The game consists of two phases: 
Phase 1-Computer Simulation Game (2 rounds). 
Participants form temporary groups with three computer players, each playing just one round, with earnings counted toward experimental compensation.
Round 1: Participants must report their project contributions for 21 scenarios where PC gamers typically contribute 0-20 MU .
Round 2: Without knowing the contributions from other computers, you directly determine your project contribution and estimate the average contribution of the other three computers (without affecting your income).

Phase 2 — Multi-round Game with Real Participants (6 Rounds). 
Participants form fixed groups with 3 real players and proceed through 6 consecutive rounds of decision-making. Each round requires determining individual project contributions while estimating the average contributions of the other 3 players (without affecting income). Throughout the process, participants are not informed of the decisions made by other players or their personal income.
